Feature: a container started from a bc-launcher image's :latest tag surfaces the correct baked versions via docker container inspect, because OCI labels and ENV inherit onto every container regardless of the run-tag

  Pins lead-5xnd (step 1 of the version-management roadmap), the runtime half of
  the provenance contract and its actual product-value statement: "so when you
  tell me about an image, I can be sure I'm using the right one." The real-world
  case is a container running from ":latest", where the originating version tag
  is NOT recoverable from the container — exactly why tags cannot carry the
  provenance. OCI labels and ENV baked at build time DO inherit onto every
  container (docker container inspect surfaces .Config.Labels and .Config.Env)
  regardless of which tag was used to run it, so the version is verifiable from
  the running container itself.

  This scenario pins that run-tag-independent OBSERVABLE — what "docker container
  inspect" surfaces on a container started from ":latest" — not the Dockerfile
  mechanism. It composes with scenario 71 (7c0c949fccdf9df2), which establishes
  that both bc-base and bc-lead carry these labels/env on the image; this
  scenario uses bc-base (the image with the known misleading "3.1.2" upstream
  label) as the representative instance, because the inheritance property is
  identical across both images. It is the load-bearing check behind bin/doctor
  (lead-q3r1) and bootstrap baked-version verify (lead-b2iz) reading the version
  from a live container. (Targets shopsystem-bc-launcher: the bc-base/bc-lead
  Dockerfiles and the publish workflow.)

  @scenario_hash:26d1817c9d115f0d
  Scenario: a container started from bc-base:latest surfaces the baked bc-launcher and shop-templates versions via container inspect, independent of the lost run-tag
    Given the published "ghcr.io/dstengle/shopsystem-bc-base" image at bc-launcher release version "v0.3.38" baking shop-templates version "v0.47.0" carries those versions as OCI labels and ENV
    And a container is started from that image addressed only by its "latest" tag, so the originating version tag is not recoverable from the running container
    When the running container is examined with "docker container inspect"
    Then the container's configured labels surface "org.opencontainers.image.version" equal to the bc-launcher release version "v0.3.38"
    And the container's configured labels surface "shopsystem.shop-templates.version" equal to the baked shop-templates version "v0.47.0"
    And the container's configured environment surfaces "SHOPSYSTEM_BC_LAUNCHER_VERSION" equal to "v0.3.38"
    And the container's configured environment surfaces "SHOP_TEMPLATES_VERSION" equal to "v0.47.0"
    And the surfaced bc-launcher version is "v0.3.38" rather than the upstream devcontainer base label value "3.1.2"
